After reading through the reviews for this dish I was curious. With 87% of people really enjoying the dish, I wondered what it was that the remaining 13% didn't appreciate about the recipe. -- I always wonder... While there are probably some who would consider me a bit liberal in doling out stars for this dish (and other recipes on this site), I know for myself that if a dish is just fair I simply don't bother to review it. That said, the recipes I review tend overall to be solidly good, wholesome, flavorful, dependable menu staples or (very rarely) are real stinkers that don't turn out according to the instructions given. As for this dish, it is really good and it is simple to prepare. Since it is also inexpensive, and didn't have the finish of boiled or reheated chicken it is hard to really have higher expectations. Heeding others suggestion that the sauce was salty, I chose to add lemon juice directly to the sauce instead of roasting the lemon slices. I also decreased the oil by half and used just a tablespoon of the butter called for. I added a few ounces of Chardonnay, which although not exactly original, did do a bit to curb the saltiness. I also soaked the capers. Lastly, I took out the chicken when it was thoroughly cooked and removed most of the olives prior to reducing the remaining sauce to a syrup. --Worked like a charm.

